					<head>Liturgy</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052" rend="visible">
						<summary>A collection of prayers, a recension of the book of Tobit and Megilat Antiochus.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052">
							<locus from="1r" to="20v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Tefilot</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">תפילות</title>
							<note>
								<p>The book of Tobit (in an unusual recension) begins on folio 12r; Megilat Antiochus begins on folio 16r.</p>
							</note>
							<decoNote type="border">
								<locus n="1r"/>1 illustrated title-page with pen flourishings, in colours.</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">Numerous text illustrations, in colours.<locus n="4r, 4v, 5v, 9r, 10r, 17r, 17v, 18r, 19r, 20r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">
								<locus n="11v"/>1 full-page drawing of a candlestick, with parts of text embodied, in colours.</decoNote>
							<incipit xml:lang="he">כתבתי זאת לכם למשמרת : באותיות יפות ומפוארות : [...] לכבוד השר החשוב האלוף איש תם וישר שמו הטוב <name type="person" role="patron">הומפרד ווענלי</name> טפסר וגיזבר הנכבד הנאמן הממונה על גנזי אוצר בית ספרי השר הגדול הקרוב למלכות הלוא הוא המלארט טרעזרי ירום הודם ותפארתם וכו' : תחת ממשלת גבירתנו המלכה המיוחסת המוצלחת אנא ירום הודה ותפארתה למעלה למעלה עד עולם א"ס:<locus n="1r"/>
							</incipit>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the second half of the 18th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>20 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>375</height>
										<width>295</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>20 folios (+ 4 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 10 leaves each.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 " ruledLines="14" writtenLines="13">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Visible hard-point ruling.</p>
									<p>Initial words written in larger characters. </p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side of the folios indistinguishable.</p>
									<p>Parts of the text written in red ink.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square script, punctuated, of the 18th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">Aharon ben Mosheh</name> of <name type="place">Poland</name>: inscribed with his name, folio 19r, 20r.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folios 19r, 20r: a scribal note of Aharon ben Mosheh, who came to England from Vilnius (The Kingdom of Poland and Lithuania), but was born in Nowogrodek.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="patron">Humphrey Wanley</name>, (b. 1672, d. 1726), Old English scholar and the librarian to the Earls of Oxford. As <name type="person">Queen Anne</name> was the subject of the Royal Prayer, the manuscript must have been completed before 01 August 1714.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Harleian binding.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Preces. Liber Tobiae. Et Alia. Hebraice. Mus. Brit. Bibl. Harl. 5713. Plut XXXI F.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1702" notAfter="1714"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">England</name>
							</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts.
Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in 1753 to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
